Ahead of the July implementation of the African Free Trade Agreement (AFTA), the Nigeria Customs Service (NCS) has appealed to the National Orientation Agency (NOA) to step up its public enlightenment activities to educate Nigerians on border policies. The AFTA opens our borders to products of other African countries without import duty and will open the flood gates for intense competition with local products and services. Director General of NOA, Dr. Garba Abari in a statement made available to LEADERSHIP by his Assistant Director of Press, Mr. Paul Odenyi after a courtesy visit to Comptroller General of Customs (CGC), Col. Hameed Ibrahim Ali in Abuja. Col. Ali said that Nigerians, particularly the border communities need to be educated on the dangers of illicit products importation and use as well as the need to cooperate with Customs in its operations. He said the technical nature of the NCS mandate requires daily education of Nigerians on issues of trade facilitation, import prohibitions, customs and excise charges. It’s necessary to work in collaboration with NOA in the area of advocacy to give the Agency’s nationwide spread. He therefore solicited that NOA’s increased his advocacy to relevant stakeholders ahead of the AFTA implementation. He directed all Customs Commands to participate fully in the active of NOA public sensitization programmes. In his remarks, the Director General of NOA, Dr. Abari stressed the need for government to explained in local languages that citizens can understand to enable the informed perspectives to the communities. He noted the agency has been adopted its sensitization on border closure. Adding that there is now yielded an overall positive disposition by the majority of Nigerians towards the policy. NOA boss explained that the visit was to explore areas of collaboration for the benefit of Nigerians and the economy, including a Patronize Made in Nigerian Goods campaign that has been flagged by the NOA.